<TEXT>
the conviction of a billionaire drug kingpin 
whose arrest in his native honduras sparked a week of riots there is 
a big victory in the war on drugs federal prosecutors said 
jurors on wednesday found juan ramon matta ballesteros guilty of 
masterminding a california drug ring linked to a colombian cocaine 
cartel 
after the conviction us attorney gary feess described the 
45yearold matta as one of the most significant narcotics 
traffickers in the world today 
assistant us attorney jimmy gurule said the federal court 
jurys decision was a message to the colombian government that if 
they extradite drug kingpins we will prosecute them to the full 
extent of the law 
matta could be sentenced to life imprisonment without possibility 
of parole feess said sentencing is scheduled for oct 5 
matta led a powerful cocaine cartel based in cali colombia that 
funneled thousands of pounds of the drug to arizona and southern 
california through mexico feess said 
he compared mattas power to that of carlos lehder rivas the 
colombian drug lord convicted earlier this year in miami 
the conviction of ballesteros is a major blow to the gangsters 
who run the international drug rings attorney general dick 
thornburgh said in a statement from washington 
the jury convicted matta on one count each of conspiracy running 
a continuing criminal enterprise and possession with intent to 
distribute cocaine and four counts of distribution of cocaine 
mattas lawyer martin stolar said he will file motions to have 
the verdict overturned and failing that will appeal he insisted 
that the case was prejudiced by publicity surrounding the 
uscolombian antidrug campaign and president bushs speech 
tuesday night 
stolar said he asked bush to delay his address but received no 
response he maintained that matta was a legitimate businessman and 
honduras largest single employer he said mattas fortune came from 
cattle ranching construction and the tobacco coffee and spice 
trade 
the us drug enforcement administration however said matta 
controlled a narcotics empire worth up to 2 billion he was accused 
of overseeing a network that distributed 72 million worth of 
cocaine in los angeles 
the case against matta stemmed from a september 1981 raid on a 
van nuys apartment complex where 19 million in cash and 114 
pounds of cocaine were sezied at that time that was the largest 
seizure of cocaine in california history 
matta became a folk hero to his impoverished neighbors in 
honduras where he granted loans bought desks for school children 
and employed about 800 people on his tobacco and dairy farms his 
extradition triggered outrage in tegucigalpa where 2000 
demonstrators burned the us embassy annex five hondurans died in 
the weeklong violence 
