<TEXT>
the government will seek the resumption of 
logging in western oregons oldgrowth forests an official said 
after a federal court lifted its ban on timbercutting in the 
northern spotted owls habitat 
conservationists who sued to prevent lumbering said that while 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals unanimous ruling wednesday 
removed the overall ban imposed june 7 it still permitted 
challenges to individual projects 
ed ciliberti the us bureau of land managements oregon 
spokesman said 66 million boardfeet of timber are ready for sale 
the injunction had forbidden timber sales within 21 miles of any 
spotted owl site identified by the bureau 
we are giving direction for our districts to begin moving those 
sales that have been enjoined ciliberti said 
if timber sales proceed conservationists will seek endangered 
species status for the owl said james monteith executive 
director of the oregon natural resources council 
the us fish and wildlife service has proposed threatened 
status for the bird a designation which would be weaker than that 
desired by conservationists 
the owl inhabits oldgrowth forests in western washington 
western oregon and northern california mostly on federal land 
scientists view it as a species whose condition indicates a forests 
overall health 
the threemember appeals court rejected conservation groups 
chief argument that new information on dangers to the owls survival 
was ignored by the blm in its environmental review the panel said 
the issue could not be raised in a lawsuit because of a federal law 
backed by the timber industry 
however the court revived sections of the lawsuit contending 
that destruction of owl habitat by logging violated federal bird 
protection law and federal and state landmanagement laws 
mark rutzick the lawyer for the timber industrys northwest 
forest resource council said the ruling offered the promise of 
final victory in the case for loggers and oregon communities that 
depend on logging 
victor sher of the sierra club legal defense fund the lead 
environmentalst attorney said its a disappointment but the 
fault is congress and not the courts we proved that the blm 
had violated the law but congress has said the courts cant hear 
the case 
the lawsuit challenged the blms refusal in 1987 to conduct a new 
environmental analysis of hundreds of planned timber sales in 
western oregon based on a new study increasing previous predictions 
of danger to the owl the bureau contended it already had taken 
adequate measures to protect the bird 
in may us district judge helen frye of portland dismissed the 
lawsuit allowing the blm to proceed with logging of 337 million 
boardfeet of timber she said the agency had failed to plan 
adequately for protection of the spotted owl but added that her 
hands were tied by federal law 
the appeals court agreed with fryes interpretation that the 
blms timber management plan could not be challenged in court on the 
basis of new information the law allowed challenges to particular 
activities in the plan 
in his opinion chief judge alfred goodwin said 
environmentalists challenge to numerous individual logging sales 
amounted to a challenge to the overall blm plan even if disputed 
sales added up to only 30 percent of the total 
the attacks on individual sales were based on a disagreement with 
the blms decision to designate certain areas for intensive timber 
management goodwin said 
that decision was made with the knowledge that owl habitat 
would be sacrificed in the clear cuts and conversion to 
secondgrowth forest he said that intentional tradeoff of 
owls for economic gain was precisely the landuse decision which is 
being challenged 
the court reinstated conservationists claims that the 
destruction of spotted owl habitat violated the migratory bird 
treaty act and federal oregon and california land management laws 
frye had dismissed those claims saying they should have been 
made while the blms timber plans were being developed but goodwin 
said environmental groups had acted as soon as they could after 
getting the new information about possible dangers to the owl 
the court ordered frye to consider the claims on their merits but 
did not impose a new injuction during that review 
