<TEXT>
by checking cancerous tissue for one protein 
doctors believe they can help predict which women with early breast 
cancer are at high risk of spreading cancer according to a report 
published today 
doctors who experimented with this approach found that by testing 
for the protein called haptoglobinrelated protein they could 
identify women who had an extremely high risk of recurrence 
they said that the presence of the protein appears to be a 
powerful primary discriminator between clinically aggressive and 
clinically indolent breast cancers its prediction power is 
dramatically improved when it is combined with information about 
the sensitivity of the tumors to the hormone progesterone 
the research was conducted by dr francis p kuhajda and 
colleagues at johns hopkins university school of medicine and 
published in the new england journal of medicine 
the study was based on 70 patients with early breast cancer who 
were treated by mastectomy from 1977 through 1985 doctors checked 
samples of their tumor tissue for the protein as well as sensitivity 
to progesterone 
overall the cancer returned in 31 women the study found that it 
recurred in 91 percent of those whose tumors produced the protein 
but were not sensitive to progesterone by contrast it recurred in 
24 percent who showed no signs of the hormone but were sensitive to 
progesterone 
doctors hope that such information will help them identify women 
who might benefit from aggressive early therapy such as 
chemotherapy and mastectomy rather than lump removal 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

