georgias 156yearold sodomy law cannot be 
applied to consenting married couples a judge ruled in clearing a 
man who spent 18 months in prison for having oral sex with his wife 
a lawyer for the american civil liberties union lauded the ruling 
wednesday as a step toward getting rid of this monstrous statute 
superior court judge robert castellani said james d moseley a 
35yearold carpenter had been imprisoned illegally he was serving 
a twoyear term 
government has no business with a married couples private 
consentual sexual practices castellani wrote moseleys right 
to marital and domestic privacy has been violated by the sodomy law 
as applied to him 
whew i feel like someone took a millstone from around my 
neck said moseley apparently the first person convicted under 
the law for conduct between marriage partners the judge had freed 
him last week pending a decision 
attorney general michael bowers said the state may appeal after 
an examination of whether the ruling might reach beyond married 
couples 
bowers said he agreed that the sodomy law cannot be applied to 
consenting married couples but the prosecutor had argued that the 
evidence suggested moseleys wife did not consent to the sodomy 
i think at least all married couples can celebrate said 
clive staffordsmith an aclu lawyer who represented moseley they 
can bring out the champagne but there are still a large number of 
nervous people in georgia who are not married 
moseleys commonlaw wife bette roberts had accused him of 
forcing himself on her and she filed a complaint in 1988 that led to 
moseley being charged with rape and aggravated or forcible oral 
and anal sodomy 
moseley denied using force and was acquitted on those counts but 
was found guilty of the lesser charge of oral sodomy after admitting 
the couple had oral sex georgia law makes oral sex a crime even 
between consenting adults 
the judge said that the jurys acquittal of moseley on the rape 
and aggravated sodomy charges meant it believed no force had been 
involved 
castellani cited a recent us supreme court ruling that upheld 
application of the sodomy law against homosexuals the majority 
decision in that case acknowledged the law might not hold up if 
applied to married couples 
