<TEXT>
the senate today approved 838 legislation 
shifting 45 million used for congressional mailings to a drug 
treatment program aimed at helping drugaddicted mothers and their 
babies 
the lopsided vote came over strong opposition from sen ted 
stevens ralaska who accused its backers of political posturing at 
the expense of lawmaker communications with constituents 
republicans proposed the measure wednesday the day after 
president bush announced a 79billion antidrug abuse campaign 
aimed at transferring the money from the account legislators use for 
their mailings the provision was offered as an amendment to a bill 
providing 2 billion for congress own expenses for fiscal 1990 
which begins oct 1 
the proposal all but eliminates districtwide mailings used often 
by senators and representatives to keep their names in their 
constituents minds but it allows members to continue answering 
individual queries 
critics said the mass mailings provided taxpayerfinanced 
publicity to incumbents making them difficult to defeat 
stevens had said wednesday that such a dramatic cut in 
congressional mailings to constituents would deprive alaskans of an 
important source of news he said many alaskans get no daily 
newspapers and learn of news from washington only from radio and 
brief television broadcasts 
we send out a postal patron newsletter to people who have no 
other source of information about whats going on in the nations 
capital stevens told his colleagues 
but stevens lured few senators to his cause during todays 
debate although sen paul simon dill did say he thought the 
amendment was not in the national interest 
seven democrats and one republican voted against the amendment 
they were bill bradley dnj ernest hollings dsc daniel 
inouye dhawaii joseph lieberman dconn spark matsunaga 
dhawaii daniel patrick moynihan dny and the republican 
stevens 
nine senators did not vote final action on the appropriations 
bill was put off until later in the day 
the measure was proposed by sen pete wilson rcalif a 
supporter of tougher efforts against drug abuse a longtime critic 
of the burgeoning costs of legislators mailings and a candidate for 
governor of california 
what we are faced with is the opportunity to not spend on 
newsletters and instead to put this money into one of the least 
wellfunded drug programs wilson said 
the money would go to a program started in 1988 that provides 
treatment to drugaddicted pregnant women focusing on those who use 
crack wilson said 400000 babies are born annually to mothers who 
use drugs 
in his tuesday evening speech unveiling the 79 billion drug 
campaign bush proposed spending 300 million for treatment 
programs he listed initiatives to help pregnant drug users as part 
of the effort but didnt specifically say how much should be spent 
for them 
without wilsons amendment the legislative spending bill would 
limit congressional spending on mail next year to 80 million 48 
million for the house which has 435 members and 32 million for 
the 100member senate 
the bill would also reduce from six to two the number of 
districtwide mailings permitted each year except for notices of 
town meetings legislators could send more but would have to pay 
for them out of the funds each receives for general office expenses 
congress is on track to spend 539 million on its mail this 
year but those expenses traditionally skyrocket during election 
years which 1990 happens to be 
the house passed a 16 billion version of the legislative 
spending bill july 31 that would provide 1247 million for 
congressional mailings 
house and senate negotiators will have to find a compromise to 
their differences over congressional mail before the bill can be 
sent to bush for his signature 
