president ranasinghe premadasas government 
bradman weerakoon the presidents foreign affairs adviser told 
reporters the government invited the peoples liberation front and 
leaders of sri lankas 23 recognized parties to the proposed peace 
conference sept 13 
we have positive responses from 10 parties we have not 
received a single negative response so for all intents and purposes 
there is a general acceptance of the governments invitation said 
weerakoon 
he said the sinhalese radicals are not among the 10 who have 
accepted but they have not rejected the invitation the group has 
rejected all previous peace overtures 
weerakoon said premadasa also had invited the liberation tigers 
of tamil eelam a dominant separatist group and other former tamil 
militant groups 
most groups of the minority tamils ended their battle for an 
independent nation in the northeast two years ago following an 
accord that promised tamils limited autonomy 
but the tamil tigers reneged on the peace plan and began 
attacking indian peacekeeping soldiers deployed to supervise the 
accord which was signed june 29 1987 at least 1000 soldiers have 
died in the fighting 
at least 10000 other people have been killed in the tamil war 
most of the deaths occurred between 1983 when the tamils took up 
arms and 1987 when the accord was signed 
after tamil agitation subsided sinhalese radicals in the south 
and center of the island began fighting to protest the accord which 
they said gives too many concessions to the minority tamils and an 
indian troop presence they charge compromises sri lankas 
sovereignty 
tamils form 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people and say 
they are discriminated against by the sinhalese who make up 75 
percent of the population and control the government most tamils 
are hindu while sinhalese are mainly buddhist 
the government says at least 5000 people have died in the 
sinhalese rebellion and blames the radicals for most deaths the 
radicals say the military and progovernment vigilante groups are 
responsible for the killings 
among the 32 people killed in the latest violence were three 
soldiers blown up in a land mine blast thursday and another shot by 
sinhalese extremists who ambushed troops bathing in a stream the 
military officials said they said they did not know who planted the 
land mine 
