<TEXT>
the flood of drugs into the united states has dried 
up since colombias latest round of violence began raising the 
price of cocaine and shrinking the size of crack rocks authorities 
said thursday 
but they warn the sudden drop in trafficking may be temporary 
and could simply be the work of middlemen trying to drive up the 
price 
the miamibased seventh coast guard district which has accounted 
for 97 percent of the more than 10000 pounds of cocaine intercepted 
by the entire service this year has seen import activity suddenly 
grind to a halt said lt cmdr jeff karonis 
were still carrying out the same operations as we were but 
the boats arent coming out and the air drops arent happening 
the targets just arent there 
pat obrien outgoing head of the us customs service in miami 
said agents from his district by far the busiest in the nation had 
been tracking three to five air drops a week prior to the colombian 
crackdown 
that has now come to a standstill he said there was only 
one right after the violence started and we werent even able to 
confirm that 
the only recent major cocaine haul 800 pounds on a freighter in 
tampa on saturday had been loaded and shipped before the violence 
began 
undercover agents trying to make cocaine buys have been put off 
for two to three weeks and even though that period is about up 
there are still no shipments ready he said the summer months have 
traditionally been the traffickers busiest 
in addition moneylaundering activity tracked by customs is 
sputtering traffickers are still moving wire transfers for old 
cocaine shipments but there are few new payments 
the drug enforcement administration has also spotted the change 
but agents there arent sure if it marks a true disruption 
yes there appears to be a slowdown of drug activity out of 
south america a fluctuation in distribution and a rise in the 
wholesale price of cocaine said miami dea spokesman john 
fernandes but we dont know if thats because of whats happening 
in colombia or if entrepreneurs are trying to take advantage of 
whats happening to raise the price 
fernandes said the price of large cocaine shipments in the last 
two weeks has increased from 1100015000 a kilogram to 
1800019000 with individual kilogram sales reaching as high as 
23000 
the scarcity is being felt on the street as well says metrodade 
police cmdr steve rothlein head of the county narcotics bureau 
street prices for a kilogram of cocaine have shot up about 7000 
he said 
crack on the other hand continues to sell for 10 dollar a 
rock but some of the rocks are getting smaller said rothlein 
obrien attributes the disruption in part to the confiscation of 
planes used to carry cocaine from processing plants in southern 
colombia to coastal staging areas 
the heads of the cartels are also having difficulties trying to 
control their operations while on the run he said but how long the 
situation lasts depends on whether the colombian government can keep 
up the pressure 
fernandes warns that the cocaine business is cyclical just like 
any other commodity operation 
there have been slowdowns before he said slowdowns at 
different intervals are normal for the narcoticstrafficking 
business 
he said other traffickers wait in the wings to replace anyone 
arrested or extradited and planes and boats can be bought again 
quickly when the pressure is off 
