<TEXT>
the state supreme court on thursday rejected 
an appeal by juan corona the farm labor contractor convicted of 
murdering 25 farm workers in 1971 
the justices unanimously denied a hearing on coronas challenge 
to a lowercourt ruling upholding his convictions he was sentenced 
to 25 years to life for each of the murders 
the bodies most of them stabbed or hacked to death were found 
in shallow graves in orchards in the marysvilleyuba city area 
defense lawyers denied coronas guilt and blamed the murders on a 
halfbrother now dead 
coronas first convictions were overturned on appeal because of a 
finding that his lawyer had acted incompetently and had a conflict 
of interest corona was convicted again at a second trial 
the 1st district court of appeal upheld the convictions in june 
despite finding that a reported confession by corona had been 
admitted into evidence improperly 
a mexican consul jesus rodriguez navarro testified at the 
second trial that corona had told him in 1978 he had killed the farm 
workers because he was a sick man 
under an international agreement consular officials cannot be 
required to testify about matters related to their official duties 
unless their government issues a written waiver the mexican 
government did not try to stop rodriguez from testifying but did not 
furnish a written waiver 
the appeals court said colusa county superior court judge richard 
patton who presided over the retrial should have excluded 
rodriguezs testimony and was wrong in deciding that the consul was 
authorized to waive the privilege of confidentiality on his own 
but the court in an opinion by justice donald king said 
coronas rights were not violated because the right of 
confidentiality was held legally by the mexican government not 
corona as a result king said the defense cannot complain that 
violation of that right deprived corona of a fair trial 
we are fully satisfied that coronas second trial was fair and 
that ultimately justice has been accomplished for both corona and 
the people of this state king said 
in seeking state supreme court review michael mendelsohn a 
lawyer for corona said hispanics were not represented adequately on 
the grand jury that indicted corona mendelsohn challenged the 
appeals courts conclusion that corona was required to show that the 
lack of hispanics had harmed his case 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

