the former chairman of the house committee that 
investigated the irancontra scandal said thursday that so many 
questions remain about the role of president bush and others that 
congress should not yet close the books on the affair 
rep lee hamilton dind asked that the house intelligence 
committee begin a continuing investigation of new documents and 
other evidence that have surfaced in the trial of former marine lt 
col oliver north or which may surface during other upcoming trials 
of irancontra figures 
congressional investigators in late 1987 concluded that top 
reagan administration officials had circumvented the law to sell 
arms to iran and generate money to buy weapons for nicaraguas 
contra rebels but the yearlong probe failed to fully pinpoint the 
extent of personal responsibility of reagan bush and others 
most importantly we still do not understand precisely what 
were the roles in these events of president reagan vice president 
bush and other top reagan administration officials hamilton said 
in a letter to intelligence committee chairman rep anthony c 
beilenson dcalif 
congress was charged with the responsibility to investigate 
these events thoroughly and to understand them as best we could we 
will have failed to discharge fully that responsibility if we leave 
important evidence unexplored hamilton wrote 
in light of the importance of the questions that remain and the 
enormous implications of the events that have occurred i do not 
believe we can consider the congressional investigation of the 
irancontra affair to be complete 
hamilton acknowledged that there is a certain weariness with the 
matter on capitol hill but noted that each new effort to dig back 
into the affair has shed new light 
he asked that as part of its continuing probe the intelligence 
panel ask the bush white house to undertake a comprehensive search 
of all relevant reagan administration files including the heads 
of state file recently discovered at the reagan library in 
california 
it is possible that other important documents were missed by 
have not yet come to light hamilton wrote 
he also asked that the committee evaluate the seven new documents 
turned up at the north trial which strongly suggested a reagan 
administration deal with the honduran government under which the 
hondurans would help the contras in return for increased us aid 
