<TEXT>
married couples are more likely to 
divorce if the woman has more education than her husband a study 
concludes 
the study found that the divorce rate for marriages in which the 
wife has more schooling than her husband is over 50 percent higher 
than it is for marriages in which the husband has the same or higher 
educational achievement 
apparently many men and women have not been socialized to 
accept the notion of a woman being educationally more accomplished 
than her husband said neil g bennett an associate professor of 
sociology at yale university who led the study 
that women are better able to support themselves and less fearful 
of going it alone could account for the higher rate of divorce 
bennett said 
we might have expected that couples who had very different 
levels of education regardless of which spouse had the higher 
education would have higher divorce rates than average because 
these couples would have different world views and be subject to 
greater conflict and stress in their marriage 
but that was not true we found only couples in which the wife 
was more educated than the husband had higher divorce rates than 
average bennett said in an interview wednesday 
in the united states about half of all marriages today will end 
in divorce 
bennetts study has not been published but the results were 
presented last month at the american sociological association in san 
francisco 
the study was based on data from nearly 3500 married or divorced 
women under age 50 collected by the national survey of families and 
households between march 1987 and may 1988 
bennett received widespread attention three years ago when he 
concluded that single collegeeducated women over age 30 had only a 
20 percent chance of getting married a census bureau researcher 
studying the same statistics disputed his findings and said those 
same women actually have a 66 percent chance of eventually marrying 
bennett has done a new study on the same subject with more recent 
data but the results will not be made public until they are 
published in november 
in looking at divorce rates the yale researchers also examined 
the effects of religious differences on marriages not unexpectedly 
they found that divorce rates are higher for couples in interfaith 
marriages 
when a wife and husband have different religion but both are not 
very religious the divorce rate is not much different from the 
average the study found 
to study the effect of educational differences the women and men 
were placed in four different educational categories those with 
less than a high school education those with a high school 
education those with some college education and those with at least 
a college degree 
bennett emphasized that men and women who marry someone who has a 
substantially different education religous belief or age are 
generally less traditional than those who marry people with similar 
characteristics and may therefore have less conventional views 
about marriage to begin with such factors however cannot be 
measured 
</TEXT>
