<TEXT>
the nonaligned movement ended its 
ninth summit conference early friday after adopting a resolution 
calling for the release of all hostages 
the fourday conference of 102 nations was attended by about 50 
heads of state and a dozen prime ministers it was due to end 
thursday but delays brought on by wrangling between hardliners and 
moderates kept the summit going until after 1 am friday 
the session passed a final declaration and adopted 30 political 
and economic resolutions dealing with topics ranging from 
afghanistan and the middle east to terrorism and drugs trafficking 
many of them were compromise resolutions reflecting the deep 
divisions among members 
the international terrorism resolution was agreed upon by the 
meetings political committee after tough bargaining 
it said the heads of state and government resolutely demanded 
that all hostages and all kidnapped persons be immediately released 
irrespective of the perpetrators and the place of the crime 
the resolution condemned all acts of terrorism perpetrated by 
individuals states or groups of states and expressed the movements 
determination to fight such acts with all possible legal means 
both nationally and internationally 
yugoslav spokesman goran milic indicated in a meeting with 
reporters at midnight that the final session was delayed about 5 
hours by disputes 
pleas for pragmatism and cooperation with the industrialized 
world contrasted with strident attacks on the united states several 
delegates denounced zionism in their speeches a topic that 
caused problems to the very end 
chairman yasser arafat of the palestine liberation organization 
insisted that in addition to the final documents stressing the 
struggle against imperialism colonialism neocolonialism racism 
and apartheid it should also condemn zionism and its 
practices 
heated arguments with moderates followed with arafat drawing 
support from such hardliners as bangladesh yemen and cuba a 
compromise was reached on including the zionism reference in one 
of the many political resolutions sources told the associated 
press speaking on condition of anonymity 
nicaragua in a bid to gain international prestige sought to get 
the summit to agree to hold its next summit there but no agreement 
was reached conference sources said 
delegates did agree however that ghana would be the site for a 
nonaligned foreign ministers conference to be held in 1991 in 
preparation of the 10th nonaligned summit 
moderates have emerged as the big majority and resisted 
throughout the summit attempts by radical nations to introduce cold 
war rhetoric 
