<TEXT>
pino daniele grew up steeped in traditional 
neapolitan music the sometimes mournful sometimes joyous melodies 
passed down for centuries in this mediterranean city 
but it didnt stop him from wanting to be elvis 
i loved rock n roll but i also loved my music neapolitan 
says the 34yearold singer i am a big fan of elvis presley and 
at the same time im a big fan of neapolitan crooner roberto 
murolo 
today daniele is leading a revival of the neapolitan song which 
made italian music worldfamous with such tunes as o sole mio 
funiculi funicula and turna a surriento return to 
sorrento 
but instead of mandolins it is electric guitars and a rock or 
jazz rhythm that mark the new neapolitan sound 
danieles albums have won him huge audiences and encouraged a 
whole school of neapolitan singers at a time when italian performers 
account for less than half the record sales in italy while american 
and british singers dominate the pop charts 
neapolitan song represents one of the main points of italian 
culture we members of the new generation said lets create a 
fusion explained daniele in an interview at his studio in 
formia 50 miles from naples 
that is we fuse it neapolitan song with modern music a 
universal language which could be jazz or rock or other kinds of 
music 
with a faded tshirt covering his husky frame his graystreaked 
black hair pulled back in a ponytail there is no mistaking daniele 
for enrico caruso but he does claim a number of other similarities 
with his neapolitan predecessors 
like them daniele sings about the sea the sultry mediterranean 
afternoons the plight of the citys poor he places special 
emphasis on melody like past neapolitans whose songs are still 
played in italian restaurants the world over 
and he uses the local dialect which is laced with french and 
spanish from naples colonial past and english from the american 
soldiers based in the area since world war ii 
in danieles songs the tradition is mixed with a rock or 
afrocuban beat something that startled people when he first began 
playing it in the mid1970s 
it was something new but it communicated emotion said the 
musician this is the important thing in the end 
indeed crowds frequently join in an emotional chorus with 
daniele particularly for his older ballads such as napule e 
naples is and terra mia my land about the corruption 
and neglect that have scarred naples 
his success has helped fuel a boom in neapolitan pop music 
featuring singers edoardo bennato teresa de sio and tony esposito 
a neapolitan massimo ranieri won the italian national song contest 
san remo last year with a new neapolitan ballad perdere 
lamore losing love 
danieles songs aim to bring together not only italian and 
american music but the experience of the poor in the two countries 
theyre neapolitan melodies but with the rhythm of american 
blacks explains gianni borgna author of history of italian 
song 
daniele suggests the poor of naples are a bit like american 
blacks not so different from outcasts in america 
the modern tunes are a long way from traditional neapolitan song 
which was influenced by arias in donizetti and rossini operas as 
well as french and spanish traditions 
daniele heard those songs while growing up as one of six children 
of a naples port worker as he taught himself to play the guitar in 
his teens he also followed singers such as peppino di capri who 
were beginning to adapt neapolitan melodies to a nightclub style 
in recent years daniele has increasingly worked with american 
and latin american musicians to experiment with other influences and 
establish broader appeal for his music 
we are trying to develop this to get into the international 
market which is very difficult he said if you dont sing in 
english youre out automatically 
he hopes nonetheless to win broader success with a 
mediterranean sound featuring neapolitan melody latin and 
blues rhythms and perhaps an english singer 
while he is not an international superstar his reputation has 
spread in europe he has given concerts in france england the 
netherlands austria and cuba 
in january he will head for the united states for a concert 
series called night of the guitar in which he will play 
instrumentals with guitarists including leslie west of mountain and 
robby krieger of the doors 
daniele says with the international contacts his songs have 
developed a more modern sound but they always have a reference to 
the neapolitan way of communicating he insisted theres always 
that 
</TEXT>
