<TEXT>
this time america cannot simply come home 
george bush speaks determinedly of victory but the fact remains 
a generation after vietnam that the united states is losing its 
second war 
again the carnage the brutality and the futility radiate nightly 
into living rooms across the land 
the scenes seem so familiar the dead being carried off in body 
bags wives and mothers grieving over senseless loss bewildered 
children ravaged by violence and disease commandos in flak jackets 
charging again and again into enemy havens only to find them 
quickly reoccupied 
this time the homefolks are not seeing these things just on 
television no matter how sickened they cannot demand that the 
politicians and the generals return their sons and daughters from 
some faraway combat zone because home is where the war is 
guerrillas are roaming the streets not of saigon but of los 
angeles and chicago and washington not the jungles of vietnam but 
the farmlands of iowa and minnesota 
bush like every president of the modern era has promised to win 
the drug war it will happen he said tuesday block by block 
child by child he has a new program latest in a long line in 
eight previous years bush by his own account was the handson 
administrator of president reagans drug war polls show most people 
believe that effort failed 
according to the drug enforcement administration crack cocaine 
has become the fast food of drugs and has spread from just three 
us cities eight years ago to virtually every state including 
rural areas now manifesting itself in all strata of society 
not a happy legacy for the crimefighting reaganbush administration 
now bush would channel 261 million into columbia and other 
andean nations to help finance the hunt for drug kingpins and their 
henchmen for whom human life is cheaper than a coca leaf 
meanwhile americas drug users are spending an estimated 100 
billion each year to keep them in business 
to this day some americans affix exclusive blame to foreign 
villains be they colombian drug lords corrupt thirdworld generals 
or jamaican immigrants a recent poll suggests a majority of the 
public would favor the use of us troops to wipe out the drug 
exporting centers around the globe 
others argue that supply only exists to satisfy demand and speak 
boldly of mandatory prison terms or hospital confinement for all 
drug abusers as if there were room for them all 
there isnt according to the american council for drug 
education 72 million americans or a whopping 37 percent of the 
population aged 12 or older have used illegal drugs at least once 
in their lifetime an estimated 145 million people had used them 
within a month of the federally sponsored national household survey 
on drug abuse last year 
an estimated 21 million americans have tried cocaine at least 3 
million are still occasional users and nearly a million are heavy 
users about 28 million people used one banned drug or another 
counting marijuana in the last year 
drugs favor no race sex or class threefourths of illicit drug 
users are white 41 percent are women including 5 million of 
childbearing age the drug education council says 11 percent of all 
babies born over the last year were exposed to illicit drugs during 
their mothers pregnancy 
drugs are in the schools the home and in the workplace eight 
percent of last years high school seniors said they had used 
cocaine over the previous year 10 percent of college students said 
they did so the drug council says 3 percent of workers between the 
ages of 20 and 40 are cocaine users in a recent survey the 
nations employers said as many as one in five workers have alcohol 
or illegal drug problems drugrelated absenteeism medical expenses 
and lost productivity are costing employers an estimated 3 percent 
of their payroll half the typical companys payment for an 
employees social security coverage 
there are some encouraging signs the national survey on drug 
abuse has found a recent decline in socalled casual drug abuse 
by young people two years ago an estimated 17 percent of college 
students were occasional users compared to 10 percent today 
but the number of heavy abusers particularly involving cocaine 
has risen sharply the percentage of weekly and daily cocaine 
users has doubled since 1986 the number of cocaineinduced deaths 
recorded by hospital emergency rooms totaled 1696 last year up 
from 604 in 1984 overall emergency rooms treated 46020 cocaine 
patients last year compared to 8831 in 1984 an increase of 421 
percent 
like the brasshat body counters in vietnam prosecutors and 
police often trumpet their battlefield victories to the news media 
seizures of vast quantities of drugs worth fortunes on the street 
massive arrests purporting to destroy this or that trafficking ring 
like lyndon johnsons tunnel light such announcements bear little 
semblance to the real course of the war 
fact is illicit drugs especially cocaine are in more plentiful 
supply at cheaper prices in more potent form than ever 
the marijuana smoked today is as much as 10 times more powerful 
than the stuff used by the flower child of the 1960s a california 
study shows the purty of cocaine sold on the streets increased from 
29 percent to 73 percent in just the two years between 1982 and 
1984 and has remained there the price has dropped to under 100 
per gram for the much purer deadlier drug 
urban slums have long been the stomping grounds of drug dealers 
but the arrival of crack a potent and cheap derivative of cocaine 
has done for those neighborhoods what gunpowder has done for beirut 
cocaine was once considered the rich mans drug with crack rocks 
selling for a mere 5 nearly anyone children included can find a 
way to obtain it 
pharmacologists say the drug itself chemically induces more 
paranoia and violence than most any other though another drug of 
choice pcp or angel dust can be as bad or worse and 
desperation among users prepared to rob and kill for the money to 
buy it and competition among sellers eager to establish 
trafficking monopolies heighten the explosive mix 
the firepower and disregard for innocent life exhibited by the 
gangs of young punks marketing crack from jamaicans in washington 
to the crips and bloods in los angeles is astonishing 
driveby killings the spontaneous murder of someone because he 
is dressed sometimes unwittingly in the colors of a rival gang 
have become commonplace in chicago the cops who raided the arms 
cache of one drug gang found the usual assortment of machine guns 
and sawedoff shotguns along with of all things a cluster bomb 
cluster bombs normally dropped from airplanes are designed to kill 
anyone within a wide area 
