for the inability of government statisticians to track significant 
changes in the economy and their effect on people and businesses 
even while spending some 2 billion this year trying 
while the skills of workers are increasingly recognized as key to 
economic growth and improving the nations competitiveness the 
government spends nearly seven times more collecting data on 
agriculture than education said the congressional office of 
technology assessment 
it seems unlikely that this is the right ratio given the 
transformation under way in the economy the agency said wednesday 
in a 40page report even worse no organization in either the 
executive branch or the congress has assumed responsibility for 
asking whether its the right ratio 
the report statistical needs for a changing us economy 
said the white house office of management and budget was told in 
1980 to set priorities and coordinate the governments 
statisticscollecting efforts 
while it has a mandate to perform this task the technology 
experts said omb has not given it much priority and has dedicated 
few resources to the effort 
efforts by agencies in the labor commerce health and human 
services and other departments to correct shortcomings have been 
hampered by white house budget officials said the report which was 
requested by the senate governmental affairs committee 
as an example it cited cuts in the budgets of most agencies for 
collecting and analyzing data during the past eight years and a 
resistance by omb officials to allow new surveys sought by 
statisticians 
these organizations are painfully aware of the problems the 
researchers said the greatest problem appears to be the absence 
of any central place in government where basic questions about 
priorities in statistics are being asked 
sen jeff bingaman dnm chairman of the senate panels 
subcommittee on government information and regulation said congress 
will likely have to force the issue when the 1980 paperwork 
reduction act comes up for reauthorization next year 
barbara clay a spokeswoman for the white house budget office 
said its officials had not seen the report and so could not comment 
on it immediately 
the congressional researchers acknowledged it has become much 
more difficult to develop meaningful statistics on economic growth 
and productivity with the emergence of an international market and a 
servicebased us economy 
the most important inputs purchased by a business may be 
research and engineering information and the skills and education of 
its employees it said the existing statistical system makes it 
extremely difficult to anticipate the potential impact of emerging 
technologies 
it cited computers and how changes in their capabilities and 
prices are reflected in the nations economic growth inflation and 
productivity figures for example it said the price of one 
megabyte of computer memory capacity fell by 95 percent between 1972 
and 1987 
measuring changes in the quality of computers however can 
seem easy in comparison with the challenge of measuring changes in 
the quality of services the report said how do you measure 
quality changes in legal services 
changes in the quality of health care and education which 
together account for more than onesixth of the nations gross 
national product are not measured at all the report said 
</TEXT>
