<TEXT>
a us district judge says that plaintiffs in the 
nations largest municipalbond default might have gotten 
significantly smaller awards had they won their case at trial 
instead of settling 
us district judge william d browning of tucson ariz on 
tuesday approved settlements to allow 750 million to be distributed 
to holders of washington public power supply system bonds in what he 
called one of the most complex lawsuits in the history of 
securities litigation 
there is more than adequate reason to conclude that the 
aggregate amount of these settlements is fully satisfactory 
given the risks associated with a full trial of the issues said 
chemical bank of new york trustee for the bondholders in a 
statement quoting the judges 106page opinion which was not 
immediately available 
it was browning who presided over the enormously complicated 
wppss litigation that in the last year resulted in settlements 
between chemical bank and defendants in the case 
the trial began a year ago in tucson but defendants reached 
settlements by january in april browning held a fairness hearing 
on the settlement in seattle 
william h berls a chemical bank vice president who has handled 
wppss matters on wednesday called brownings ruling a carte 
blanche approval of the negotiated settlements 
this is a major milestone in the wppss litigation he said 
the bondholders are just one step away from distribution of the 
settlement money 
the final step is for browning to schedule a distribution 
hearing at which attorneys will argue precisely how the funds 
should be distributed berls said no such hearing has been 
scheduled he said 
in determining the distribution the judge will emphasize when 
each bondholder purchased the bonds berls said the plaintiffs in 
the case essentially broke down into two types of bondholders those 
who purchased their bonds before the default on june 15 1983 and 
those who bought bonds afterward 
in 1983 wppss defaulted on 225 billion in bonds it had sold to 
finance construction of a nuclear power plant at the hanford nuclear 
reservation in eastern washington and another at satsop west of 
olympia wppss had abandoned construction of those two plants in 
1982 because of rising construction costs and doubts about the need 
for the plants power 
the default was triggered by a washington state supreme court 
ruling that the participating utilities lacked the legal power to 
sign contracts with wppss guaranteeing payment even if no 
electricity was generated 
dozens of lawsuits were combined into one action against wppss 
all 88 utilities that contracted with the consortium to build the 
two reactors engineering firms wall street bond underwriters 
utility and wppss directors and a consulting firm 
the settlements approved require the defendants to pay 580 
million into the chemical bankadministered settlement fund 
together with 107 million in settlements approved earlier plus 
interest the amount available for distribution in december would be 
750 million berls said 
berls said chemical bank was not worried that browning would have 
exercised his other option that of rejecting the settlements 
brownings ruling validated all the actions weve taken 
berls said 
i think the court by taking the action it did endorsed the end 
we were all trying to reach which was peace he said 
wppss paid no money in the settlement in exchange for cooperation 
from its employees at the trial plaintiffs attorneys said there 
wasnt enough money left in wppss to pursue 
wppss was building five nuclear reactors to generate electricity 
in the late 1970s but only one was completed two remain 
mothballed for construction to resume if enough demand 
materializes for the electricity they would produce 
 
</TEXT>
