<TEXT>
three exheirs to the pacific lumber co 
have filed suit against drexel burnham lambert inc of new york 
charging fraud during the financing of a hostile buyout of the 
company 
the suit filed wednesday in humboldt county superior court said 
stanwood murphy jr suzanne murphy and warren murphy received 40 a 
share for stock that was actually worth more than 70 a share it 
seeks 18 million from drexel to cover the difference 
the murphys are descendants of simon j murphy who bought 
pacific lumber in humboldt county in 1905 it was bought by texas 
investor charles hurwitzs maxxam group in 1985 
the suit also names as defendants former drexel junkbond king 
michael milken and former wall street financier ivan boesky who the 
suit claims secretly bought stock for drexel 
the suit claims a scheme to take over the lumber company at a 
cheaper price was worked out in secret talks in the spring of 1985 
between drexel and unnamed maxxam officals hurwitz was not named as 
a defendant in the suit 
according to the lawsuit drexel knew it would be able to sell 
these shares to maxxam through boesky at a profit but did not 
disclose its intentions 
the suit contends that at the time maxxam was attempting the 
takeover drexel filed a false affidavit indicating that it did not 
own any pacific lumber stock 
the suit contends drexel owned more than 5 percent of the redwood 
lumber company with boesky acting as its representative 
pacific lumbers articles of incorporation required 80 percent 
shareholder approval of a merger deal if any stockholder owned more 
than 5 percent of the company maxxam held about 46 percent of the 
companys stock 
since drexel concealed its stake during the takeover attempt 
shareholders assumed that the maxxam bid needed only 51 percent 
shareholder approval the suit contends many shareholders 
believing they would be unable to stop a simplemajority approval 
decided to sell to maxxam the suit maintains 
the suit says that concern that the drexel affidavit was false 
surfaced in september of 1988 when the securities and exchange 
commission filed charges against drexel in a celebrated 
securitiesfraud case 
drexel has agreed to settle that case by pleading guilty to six 
felony fraud counts and paying a 650 million fine 
boesky is serving a federal prison sentence after pleading guilty 
to unrelated securitieslaw violations los angelesbased milken 
former head of drexels junkbond unit has been charged with 
separate securities violations 
drexel officials could not be reached for comment 
