talks on opening south koreas closed 
telecommunications market to the united states bogged down thursday 
with both sides showing few signs of compromise officials said 
the seoul talks were called after the united states named south 
korea as an unfair trader in telecommunications in february under 
the 1988 trade act calling for tough retaliatory trade sanctions 
the meeting began wednesday and continued until late thursday 
night but there was little chances of agreement said officials at 
the communications ministry 
gordana earp the chief us delegate asked south korea to 
announce a timetable to open its market before july 1 next year but 
seoul officials refused to comply saying their telecommunications 
industry needs two or three more years to grow the ministry 
official said 
south korea expressed willingness to accept parts of washingtons 
demands to open its market to us telecommunications equipment but 
refused to allow direct us investment in the market for 
valueadded networks the official said 
earp strongly indicated that washington may impose trade 
sanctions against south korea unless its demand was fully accepted 
he said 
the telecommunications talks were the first in a series of 
intensive trade negotations scheduled in the coming months between 
the two countries 
seoul officials are concerned that washingtons trade pressure 
will get tougher in the coming months when us vice president dan 
quayle commerce secretary robert mosbacher and trade representative 
carla hills visit seoul 
mosbacher is scheduled to visit seoul sunday through tuesday to 
discuss wideranging trade issues presumably with emphasis on south 
koreas marketopening measures 
mosbacher is expected to seek to further open south koreas 
agricultural market to us beef and other farm products and demand 
seouls stricter protection of us intellectual property rights 
korean officials said 
the two countries signed an agreement for protection of 
intellectual property rights in 1985 but the united states has 
complained that south korea neglected its strict enforcement 
mosbacher is also expected to raise a plan by du pont co to 
construct a 150 million plant in south korea 
south korea under washingtons pressure opened its market to 
243 us agricultural products in may but the united states says the 
action was not enough accoring to seoul officials 
south korea is washingtons second largest agricultural market in 
the world after japan it imported 23 billion worth of us farm 
products last year 
washington ran a trade deficit of 85 billion with south korea 
last year 
