<DOCNO> AP890907-0274 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
government farm programs must encourage 
alternative methods of food production that save the soil and use 
fewer chemical fertilizers weedkillers and pesticides a national 
research council report said thursday 
federal farm policies have generally made a plentiful food 
supply a higher priority than protection of the nations soil and 
water resources the report said 
instead of supporting environmentally benign ways of 
producing food the report said government programs have worked 
against those alternative methods 
linda worthington a coordinator for americans for a safe food a 
subsidiary of the private nonprofit center for science in the 
public interest said she agreed with the reports charge that 
government farm policies have been an impediment 
some of the basic agricultural policies that have been in 
motion almost since world war ii have pushed the american farmer 
into a highchemical method of farming and makes it difficult if 
not impossible for the farmer to move into more sustainable 
practices she said 
worthingtons group earlier this year released a study showing 
that efforts to promote organic and lowchemical farming is 
flourishing at the state level while the federal effort is moving 
slowly 
the latest report alternative agriculture came after a 
threeyear 625000 study by a 17member committee headed by john 
pesek of iowa state university the council is an agency of the 
national academies of sciences and engineering 
as used in the 450page report alternative agriculture is not a 
single system of farm production with a siple list of dos and 
donts it is a generic term that includes a wide range of 
methodology and labels organic biological lowinput 
regenerative sustainable 
the usda uses its own acronym lisa for lowinput sustainable 
agriculture in a bid to help farmers find lowercost ways of 
producing crops and livestock while helping protect the environment 
assistant secretary charles e hess said at usda that congress 
has already authorized a number of program changes to give more 
choices to farmers and that flexibility will be an important part of 
drafting a 1990 farm bill to replace the 1985 law 
hess told reporters that the agriculture department also has 
expanded its work in ipm or integrated pest management which uses 
a variety of methods to control crop pests instead of the old 
practice of dousing fields with pesticides 
the report recommended that the department boost its spending on 
lisa to at least 40 million a year from the current level of 445 
million hess said the total usda research budget is about 12 
billion this year and that a substantial upgrading of that is under 
review 
hess acknowledged that there has been a major step forward in 
the last five years in the recognition of alternative farm 
methods this has been a shared repsonsibility of usda the 
landgrant universities and congress he said 
only a few of the nations 217 million farms have adopted entire 
alternative systems of production but the report said the need is 
there and that bits and pieces have been successfully used 
hess said there is no magic formula and the practices will 
vary from farm to farm 
crop rotations in which soilbuilding crops are grown after the 
production of corn or other grain for several years are examples of 
alternative methods the conventional method might call for the same 
crop year after year with farmers heaping on costly chemicals to 
boost production 
many federal policies discourage adoption of alternative 
practices and systems by economically penalizing those who adopt 
rotations apply certain soil conservation systems or attempt to 
reduce pesticide applications the report said 
federal programs often tolerate and sometimes encourage 
unrealistically high yield goals inefficient fertilizer and 
pesticide use and unsustainable use of land and water it said 
many farmers in these programs manage their farms to maximize 
present and future program benefits sometimes at the expense of 
environmental quality 
a primary goal of commodity program reform should be the 
removal of the existing disincentives that discourage alternative 
methods of production 
this step would ensure that farmers who employ crop rotations 
and recommended resource conservation practices are not deprived of 
farmincome support the report said 
thus it added congress would have to revise existing programs 
to eliminate penalties for farmers adopting crop rotations and to 
allow more flexibility in substituting or adjusting acreage 
allotments to accommodate rotations 
the american farmland trust a nonprofit conservation group 
based in washington said the report documents the compatibility 
of economic concerns and conservation measures on the nations 
farms 
today many farmers successfully implement safe sustainable 
agricultural practices said ralph grossi aft president 
however there is no widespread coordination of these efforts 
the study was financed mainly by a 410000 grant from the wk 
kellogg foundation other private contributors put up the balance 
and the usda provided 80000 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the committees report alternative agriculture is available 
from the national academy press 2101 constitution ave nw 
washington dc 20418 for 1995 per paperback copy prepaid or 
2995 for hardcover 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

