<TEXT>
senate majority leader george j mitchell said 
thursday he will vigorously oppose a capitalgains tax cut which he 
called a giveaway to the rich that would have to be financed by 
middleincome taxpayers 
mitchell said he favors preferential tax treatment for capital 
gains but only as part of a fair progressive tax structure that 
would include raising the maximum tax rate paid by wealthier 
americans on all types of income 
the present proposal is unfair unwise and will increase the 
deficit mitchell dmaine told reporters it will require 
middleclass taxpayers to make up that tax break for the wealthy 
mitchell cited estimates that on average a capitalgains 
reduction would be worth 31000 a year to a person with income over 
200000 
the house ways and means committee is expected to approve a 
capitalgains cut next week 
until passage of the 1986 tax overhaul capital gains which are 
profits from the sale of stock and other investments were taxed at 
a lower rate than other income but the capitalgains preference 
as well as such breaks as deductions for sales taxes and universal 
individual retirement accounts was taken away so that tax rates on 
all kinds of income could be cut significantly 
president bush promised during the campaign last year to restore 
the preference for capital gains arguing such action would spur 
investment and saving he has asked congress to cut the maximum 
capitalgains rate now 33 percent to 15 percent 
a compromise reduction which has the presidents support was 
proposed by rep ed jenkins dga it would cut the top rate for 2 
years to 20 percent then raise it permanently to 28 percent and 
ensure that profits caused solely by inflation would not be taxed 
jenkins plan has the backing of a bare majority of the house 
ways and means committee but the panels democratic leadership has 
delayed a vote in an effort to win support for a third plan 
offered by rep dan rostenkowski dill the new proposal would 
index the value of investments so that inflationcaused gain 
would not be taxed but it would go a big step further for assets 
held for five or more years exempting from taxation as much as half 
the price for which such an investment is sold 
mitchell said that because of the budget deficit this is not the 
time to consider any cut in capitalgains taxes asked if he is 
prepared to go to the mat in opposition to a cut he stomped his 
foot and replied yes 
he said that if a preference is voted for capital gains that 
would increase pressure to restore other breaks that were taken away 
in the 1986 overhaul 
coincidentally sens alfonse damato rny and christopher 
dodd dconn introduced a bill thursday that would restore 
slightly modified but fully deductible iras for all workers a 
worker regardless of income could avoid tax on up to 2000 per 
year contributed to an ira one with an unemployed spouse could 
contribute another 1000 
the worker would be allowed a tax credit for 15 percent of the 
ira contribution thus one who made the maximum 2000 contribution 
could save 300 in taxes 
the 1986 law retained fully deductible iras only for those not 
covered by a company pension regardless of income and couples 
earning less than 35000 and single workers earning less than 
25000 
