<TEXT>
an experimental vaccine for a venereal disease 
that kills unborn calves appears to be controlling the illness that 
causes an estimated 500 million in losses annually nationwide a 
researcher said thursday 
within the next two or three months well begin to get a much 
better idea of just how efficient this product is said bill 
kvasnicka nevada extension veterinarian but at this point 
everything points toward the fact that this is going to be an 
extremely good vaccine for use in the field 
we see it as a major breakthrough to controlling this disease 
the vaccine for the sexually transmitted trichomoniasis is now 
available in 41 states under conditional license from the us 
department of agriculture researchers estimate the vaccine reduces 
the incidence of trichomoniasis by more than 90 percent 
kvasnicka mark hall a microbiologist at the university of 
nevada school of medicine and don hanks department chair at unrs 
veterinary medicine department began developing the vaccine a few 
years ago 
nevadas cattlemen asked us to develop something because so 
many cattle were infected with this disease said kvasnicka 
citing statistics that 441 percent of nevada cattle tested positive 
for the disease in 1987 
adult cows dont show symptoms of the disease when infected with 
trichomoniasis thats spread during breeding but cows with the 
illness can become infertile abort or their fetuses die kvasnicka 
said 
