<TEXT>
seven large companies will offer athome 
emergency child care to more than 13000 employees in a yearlong 
experiment in daycare assistance 
the employees will qualify for emergency assistance in a variety 
of situations that typically force parents to stay home from work 
when a child becomes ill and cannot go to school when the familys 
regular child care arrangements fall through or when a parent is 
suddenly called away on business an employee will be entitled to 
use the service up to three consecutive days 
this is a perfect example of what i have in mind when i write 
about the concept of the familyfriendly workplace edward f 
zigler a yale professor and a longtime advocate of a national child 
care policy told the new york times in a story published thursday 
the seven companies all in new york are home box office 
colgatepalmolive national westminster bank usa the time inc 
magazine co the accounting firm ernst amp young the electric 
utility consolidated edison co and skadden arps slate meagher amp 
flom new york citys largest law firm 
a mixture of bottomline profit considerations and concern for 
employees spurred companies to create the program officials said 
we no longer live in communities where there are extended 
families or where we even know our neighbors so parents have no 
backup systems said karol rose manager of the work and family 
program at time 
when an employee doesnt come to work or leaves a child in a 
situation he worries about it is stressful for the employee and 
costly for the employer 
five participating companies will pay the full cost of the care 
about 1050 an hour and the others will pay most of the cost with 
employees covering the balance 
some companies expect the program to cut costs because of the 
high cost of temporary workers for example home box office pays 
15 to 20 an hour to hire a temporary word processor said nancy 
platt a company spokeswoman 
