<TEXT>
chemical giant du pont de nemours amp co has been 
ordered to stop selling two fungicides which were contaminated with 
an herbicide during manufacture the us environmental protection 
agency announced thursday 
the two fungicides benlate and tersan were contaminated with 
atrazine during manufacture by a subcontractor terra chemicals of 
blythe ark said spokesman pete bentley of the epa philadelphias 
office 
use of the tainted fungicides poses potential risks of plant 
injury and illegal residue on food crops the epa reported benlate 
is registered for use on ornamental plants and certain food crops 
while tersan is registered for turf and ornamental uses 
bentley said since atrazine is applied early in the growing 
season residue from the pesticide is not normally found on crops 
because of that tolerance standards for atrazine residue have not 
been established by the epa 
benlate however is applied later in the growing season and 
because of that atrazine residue could show up bentley said 
however the contamination does not pose a significant health 
threat he said 
the epa issues between 1000 and 2000 stopsale orders a year 
and the move is not considered unusual bentley said 
du pont spokesman sam waltz said most of the product has already 
been sold and the company initiated a voluntary recall last month 
the epa issued the stopsale order after receiving numerous 
complaints of plant injury nationwide bentley said because 
atrazine is an herbicide the contaminated benlate was killing some 
of the plants it was applied on 
